column2: Migrated from EPA STORET Legacy Database- originally reported by Wisconsin DNR
Taylor lake has a bad area where the run-off from king veterans home comes in.  Assumed sample time was noon.
It rained the night of the 21st and was raining when readings were made on the 22nd.
Very busy Sunday afternoon- low 80s- partly cloudy.
Late day Sunday- low 70s- clear to partly cloudy and windy.
Mid week- 70 degree range- clear.  Windy.  Lakes appreciating lack of boat traffic.
Beautiful late Spring day- clear skies- temps in the uppers 70's- moderate winds.  Tests taken by myself and my husband- Bob Wells.

The lake was very stirred up- we purpusfuly waited a day to let the water settle down before testing.  The day was perfect.  Very little boat traffic- clear skies- light breeze air temp around 80.  The results came back bad- these lakes are to abused and overcrowded and it showed to obviously with this set of tests.  Wild life is disappearing- the loons we had all Spring have now moved away.  Small batches of geese and ducks- with very few babies.  The clarity of the water was poor- our once beautiful water looked not so healthy yesterday.

Lake was not coming along as far as color and clarity as we had hoped it would be- very little improvement in clarity.  More of a darker green detected.  These lakes can't take this abuse.  Loons have been gone now for over a month- only an occasional sighting- used to be several times daily- the loons lived on Sunset and Rainbow Lakes until approx. the 4th of July- that is when the boating population went out of control.  To many boats- to big of boats allowed- wave action tearing the shores apart- very sad to see and none of the organizations affiliated with the lakes will do a thing.  So very sad

Beautiful- clear fall day.  Temp in the mid 60's.  The lakes are not clearing up as quickly as I had hoped- maybe due to the wonderful warm weather and continued moderate use of the Chain.  My husband- Bob Wells helped with the testing and a friend- Brett Wilke had his first experience doing the temperatures.
